      "yaml": "# Read-conformance fixture — load a checked-in v2 table and observe it.\n#\n# source: artifact means the runner does NOT build the table from an op-log; it\n# materializes the checked-in bytes/ (restoring them to the pinned root named in\n# bytes/ROOT) and loads the table read-only, then runs the observe entries. This\n# is the read side of the same contract: the observe -\u003e decode -\u003e canonical-emit\n# half is identical to the write (synthesized) fixtures.\n#\n# The bytes/ tree was minted by running fixtures/v2_append_timetravel through the\n# DML runner into the pinned root — so this fixture and its write sibling share a\n# golden's row-state, demonstrating that write-conformance mints read-conformance.\n\nheader:\n  id: v2_read_append_timetravel\n  format-version: 2\n  spec-anchor: \"table-spec#snapshots\"\n  source: artifact\n  artifact:\n    path: .        # bytes/ lives alongside this fixture.yaml\n\nentries:\n  # read the current table state (the two appends of the sibling write fixture)\n  - op: observe\n    at: latest\n    expect:\n      scan:\n        rows:\n          - { id: 1, category: a }\n          - { id: 2, category: b }\n          - { id: 3, category: a }\n"
